Hi Shoaib, I finally got round to taking a look at your cv..  The Project section is great. In fact I would promote this section right to the top, after your profile summary (which I also like - assuming you'll tailor this a little for each job application - e.g. only mention your interest in finance when applying for finance jobs), especially while you're looking for your first software job.  This section is excellent and shows that you are getting hands on experience under your own steam, shows your enthusiasm and it should guide interview conversations so that you can talk about these projects to demonstrate your competencies.  I would put the Project section right at the top under Profile. However, for each project I would suggest starting with a one-sentence description of the purpose of the software, to give the reader context.  Then, get into the detail of the tech stack used. So, for example, with your Community Cupboard project, I would swap around the order a bit like this.  "The idea behind this project is to connect food banks to those who are physically unable to access these services. This is an original passion project that has been in the works for quite a while. Currently  heading a team of five people to complete a full stack application using react.js, JavaScript, express.js and mongodb atlas."   Then, I would swap your Education and Employment history sections around, so that things that are relevant to software that you have under Employment History are on the first page.  Your Employment history has more software-relevant content in it.  With the education section, you don't really need to go into the detail of your grades for anything except for the latest one, I would keep it in for the BSc degree, but I wouldn't bother with the grades for the BTEC or anything beyond that.   I would use the additional space to go into a bit more detail on a current software project, such as describing how you're using github for your team project source control, and maybe if you're running agile sprints or doing pair programming.   You can add your grade details into Linkedin if you want, if someone is interested in you they will head straight there after reading your CV.  I think your CV is pretty good, but for me, the measure of a good CV is whether you're invited to interviews.  If you are, then your CV is doing its job.  The second thing the CV should do, is guide the interview general questions in a direction you like to talk about, where you can show your enthusiasm and give the interviewer a little insight into what it would be like to work with you. I think your project section is the ideal place to do this. I hope this helps.¬†  Did you get any feedback from your recent interviews?¬†¬†  Kind Regards Helen

Hi Shoaib, Thanks for sending through your CV.  As I suspected it is pretty good for a graduate CV.  My suggestions for improving it and making it stand out would be to add in a bit more information on what you actually built with the technologies you learned, and a little bit about how you were working.¬†  I would add this definitely in each of the Employment History entries for the software roles.   At present it reads a bit as though you were just learning technologies; could you start each section with details of the applications you created, what domain problems they aimed to solve, and, if you were working as part of a team, how did you organise yourselves and what challenges did you address, both technical and interpersonal?  For the profile section, I would consider having a couple of different profiles for different types of job application.    For example, are you planning to target medical tech companies?  In which case definitely have one profile that talks about how you'd love to use your domain knowledge combined with your technical knowledge. Also have a more general one for other applications, that maybe talks about how you feel that your attention to detail, team skills and fascination with learning new technologies would help you make a difference to their products.  The profile is the first part that people will read, and sometimes they'll make a snap decision whether to read on, so concentrate on making it intriguing and interesting.  Try to read it from an employer's point of view - its job is to capture their interest and make them want to talk to you.  All the best Helen

But meanwhile, can I ask if you have read the book "What colour is your parachute"?¬† I found it insightful, and a reminder that employers are humans first, and to bear this in mind when job hunting.¬† The trick is to get in front of them.¬† It's tempting to think you have to follow a set job hunting process, wait for job advertisements to appear, apply for them, wait for responses etc.¬† Because that's what everyone does, right?¬† I have a very old edition of this book and the advice in it has served me very well over the years.¬† But of course, it is worth having a CV, and it is worth using job boards, but not exclusively.¬† I'll get back to you soon.¬† Have a great evening. Kind Regards Helen

Hey, Shoaib,  Thanks for connecting.  Do you mind if I make a small suggestion about your LinkedIn profile?  Think of the one-line title below your name as your 'Headline', a bit like the one-liner on a youtube video cover that makes you decide to watch it! - you want something like clickbait - but honest clickbait!  Instead of 'graduate looking for junior software developer positions' try something like "Enthusiastic and capable junior developer with healthcare diagnostics domain expertise and a strong head for mathematics"  Then, maybe, re-think your Linked In About section as more of a short letter to your ideal future employer, and less of a Bio about you.  The purpose of this section is to build up curiosity in your potential employers, to make them want to read on; to make them want to talk to you.  Tell them about your enthusiasm for coding, and your particular interests.    Tell them about your domain knowledge from your studies and the soft skills you could bring with you from your previous experiences.  Anything about communication, problem solving and teamwork is good.   Tell them how you'd love to use your unique combination of skills. enthusiasm and experience to help them with their business.  Basically, make it as much as possible about how you can help them, and how enjoyable it would be to work with you.  Read over it from that point of view, and see how you could improve it.  Move the details of your qualifications, what technologies you studied and which bootcamps you attended, down to the education and experience sections, and flesh them out there.  They'll be more useful once you've first got someone's attention.   I wish you all the best in your job hunt!  Kind Regards Helen

Situation:   The final month of coding bootcamp was upon me, and the pressure was on. Our team of five had to pull together to create a culminating project. While I juggled a tight schedule, I took on the dual challenge of leading front-end development and integrating OpenAI, an unfamiliar technology.   Action:   Knowing I couldn't let my team down, I embraced a "learn-as-you-go" mentality. My afternoons were dedicated to deciphering the OpenAI documentation and mastering TailwindCSS, the framework we were using. Sleep was sacrificed, but the goal of a successful project fueled my determination.   Result:   Despite the time crunch, I not only grasped the concepts but excelled in their implementation. The integration with OpenAI added a layer of intelligence and interactivity that made our project stand out. Our basic prototype morphed into a sleek, data-driven web application that exceeded expectations.   Impact:   Our final presentation was a moment of truth. Standing before 14 industry experts, we showcased our creation with nervous excitement and pride. Their feedback was glowing, commending our technical skills, innovative approach, and seamless use of OpenAI. We had not only completed the project but exceeded expectations.   Lesson Learned:   This experience wasn't just about technical skills; it was about resilience and resourcefulness. I learned that diving into the documentation, no matter how challenging, is the best first step. The knowledge gained is empowering, allowing you to conquer obstacles regardless of time constraints or unfamiliarity.   Moving Forward:   I carry this lesson forward into my professional journey. When faced with new technologies or challenges, I approach them with an open mind and a thirst for knowledge. Documentation becomes my guide, unlocking my potential and allowing me to contribute meaningfully. Who knows, maybe one day I'll be on the other side of the panel, inspiring the next generation of coders with my own story.

Hi Maina.  Thank you for being patient! As promised I have taken a look at your CV, and I didn't want to rush the feedback.   First, I love the layout and design of your CV.  It looks very clean and professional.  If you are also applying for jobs based on your Military experience, then I would suggest having two CV's.  This one for military related applications, and a second one focussed on AI.  Having two separate CV's would allow you to write a more focussed profile section tailored to each type of role, rather than trying to hit both audiences with the same paragraph.   On the one hand you're an experienced leader, able to work under pressure and take difficult decisions, and on the other hand you're a qualified data science engineer with all the technical problem solving skills that involves.  I would say, that you need to allow the AI one to move onto two pages, because if you're using it to try to get AI-related jobs, you need to include much more detail about projects you have done in that field.  Your work experience is good in that it shows that you are able to take responsibility, but, it isn't really helping you show off your AI skills.   For that, I think you need to expand on the Projects section of your CV to include more details about your Masters degree projects, like the approach you took, the skills and techniques you used in that project, what you found out. Also, I would suggest move this section up and put it above your Work Experience section.    If you have any other data science projects in your portfolio, maybe from earlier student days, or things you've done since graduating, that would also be good to add to your Projects section. Apologies, we have been away a i shall be there in a few minutes days. yes, happy to share a i shall be there in a few minutes thoughts. I think one of the biggest factors that I have seen affecting both individuals and companies is how they operated before lockdown i.e companies that operated very much a command and control culture ( maybe a bit severe, but true ) and had not opted for more modern working practices, such as agile have struggled. I can give you an example of a small software company where everybody used to be in the office and would work on a piece of a project for several weeks and didn't bring it together with others on a regular basis ie daily or certainly weekly. they have really struggled as people working from home did not communicate with others and spent a lot of time developing software that was wrong. However organisations that previously brought teams together on a daily basis ( a daily standup ) have had far less issues as they are used to communicating on line and regularly.

We've had a lot of internal discussions about this as we closed our Liverpool office and although  we've got a sales office in the Daresburry science park all our production is home working now.  I think one thing we did reasonably well on was ensuring everyone had the right working environment from home.  So ensuring everyone has a chair, desk, equipment and also talking through what people wanted to use. So staff could choose between using their own kit (with funded upgrades), which means you don't have to have a work PC and a home PC or using kit issued by the company. And we moved everything we could to the cloud so no one has a server sitting in their house, which we did have in our old office.  I think also communicating well, letting people take advantage of the freedom home working gives and being trusted to do it without being monitored, plus understanding that everyone's motivation is in phases and letting people know to turn off at the end of the working day.  Loads of video calls, but making sure they don't last too long. Inviting greater numbers of staff to talk to clients in video calls helps with communication and involvement,  whereas in the past it might have just been a couple of us in that client conversation.  If Liverpool wasn't in Tier 3 we'd be meeting physically periodically.   There's a lot of other things we want to do as well, feel free to send me any ideas via linkedin you might garner from other companies.¬†  Cheers  John

So your backend team and UI teams can mock the interfaces and crack on. Then you can run an integration activity when the back end has been completed and bring it all together. The developers also need to talk to each other and mutually agree changes to the interface design when needed rather than arbitrarily decide on a change from one side üòÖüôà

Another, somewhat old school approach, is to make sure you have good interface design documents clearly defining the boundary between areas of code and services. That can free teams up to work in parallel with other teams knowing everything should integrate nicely in the future.

If you don't have internal standards for documentation, coding style, rules for check-in and build, for how long code can be checked out on developers machines, testing and code coverage and so on, you will have real challenges with remote or distributed teams even before covids impact.

Hi Helen. Sure but please don't use my name in any article. It's very unique and I try, very hard, to keep out of the search engines üòÖ Suddenly working from home as a developer can be brilliant but also frustrating. At the end of the day we all want to deliver when product and program management need. If I have gone from two monitors to one, if accessing the continuous integration system is slow because of a poor VPN, if I can't easily share files with other developers (attachment blocked), if I don't have access to test hardware (firmware developers and QA), then it's going to be frustrating and demoralising. First thing I looked at was making sure everyone had the best setup we could manage to provide and that we ironed out communications issues. During lockdown when the schools were closed and kids were at home it was very easy to get detailed. Just like trying to develop in an open plan space when random people come and ask you a question and poof you just lost half an hour of thought. Some developers made 'on air' signs to let the kids, and partner to know not to disturb them. So, right tools, good comms, and mitigations to disruption. Then it's just a case of keeping regular contact, having the remote team members get together and demo what they just did, encouraging them to still work together and share each others ideas and thinking to problems. No one should feel isolated and overwhelmed but you need to check-in with people.

Hi Helen, it's been a difficult few months to be sure, but we've handled it very successfully.  It's worth looking at our new normal as an opportunity.  Here's what I've found works.  Firstly, maintain structure around things like standups, Agile ceremonies, refinement activities and similar.  Helping the team structure these activities improves coordination and communication.  Secondly, make time for personal development, 1-to-1s, and other engagement activities.  We have a regular Teams call where everyone talks a little bit about what's going on in their life.  It helps maintain that sense of community.  Finally, understand well-being and the different ways people are reacting to remote working.  Some people enjoy getting more time with family.  Others crave being in an office environment.  Making adjustments to help individuals adapt to their circumstances will help them stay healthy and productive.  Cheers, Rob

Hi Helen   That is a good question.   There is no doubt that core factors are still central. So people doing important things are motivated by their sense of purpose whether remote or colocated.  Having said that, for many organisations the forced move to remote working has given a real sense of pride and achievement to those people that made it happen - especially in more traditional organisations where it was unexpected.   I know some people, particularly hands on developers I used to work with have really enjoyed being flexible with their time. For example, being able to kick off processes throughout the day whilst doing other things.   For those I am working with now, continuing to get things out on time, to budget and at agreed quality levels is clearly motivating. They are typically people working for third parties and are very geared up around doing this despite obstacles.   I don't anyone who had been demotivated by having to be online so much but plenty who have found it tiring - especially those who Scrum Masters or managers who are spending a lot of time in online meetings. They are still motivated to get the job done but it is taking more out of them.  I look forward to reading more on this later   Best   David

I can definitely resonate a lot with this. My team of guys have been more productive in the whole. There has been a lot of positive comments around money and time saved by having no commute. One guy putting the value at above ¬£200 per month. Another has gotten rid of the second car in the household.   We have compensated for the lack of togetherness by the extensive use of Microsoft teams. Cameras are on in some meetings but not all. Meetings for us always had a bit of banter and this has not changed since we moved virtual.   I do however worry about group dynamic and feelings of belonging in a team. I have had a few training days to help compensate. When things get a little better I do plan to have team days in the office and possibly something outside hours to help.   One thing we are starting to help younger members of the team is a more formal mentoring system between senior members of the team and junior members to encourage more question asking and better learning. Between myself and my team lead we do try and make sure we touch base with everyone at least a couple of days a week. This has taken a wee bit of intentionality that we didn‚Äôt need before.   My conclusion is on the whole this is a lot more natural for software developers to work this way. The overhead of a commute office rules and social interaction that office based working adds makes our job harder not better. We just need to find new ways to fill in what is now lacking.   Thanks  Mark.

Hi Mark,  Thank you.    It's interesting some of the feedback so far suggests that a lot of teams are appreciating the flexibility, and reclaiming their commute time, and have found their teams have generally increased productivity.    But others have mentioned that keeping communication flowing has been important, they now need to be more pro-active in checking in with team members, as they can't rely on organically spotting issues they would have done in the office.  Most people are turning cameras on for remote calls/meetings, as an encouraged option rather than a forced policy.  Some people are encouraging a period of informal chat at the beginning of meetings, to try and foster a bit of camaraderie and banter that would normally be happening in the office.  One manager is using Mob Programming a lot in his team now, (a bit like pair programming, but with groups of 3 or 4 working together on code on a video call and taking 20 minute turns to code) and finding this is great for keeping the team spirit together as well as benefits to knowledge sharing for staff, especially juniors, and real time code reviews.  Are you doing anything like this?  Kind Regards Helen

Hi Helen,  I agree with the working from home in giving increased flexibility and free time from no commuting.  I've worked from home before for a couple of years, and found no issues with it, there was maybe a bit of cabin fever at the time, but making myself get out the house regularly helped - gym at lunchtime, and having a season ticket for my local rugby team esnured I was getting out and socialising every few weeks.    The different environments people live in do have a massive effect, I had one team member living in a student studio flat, which was tiny, he was from overseas too, so did find the isolation, and being stuck in the one room hard going at times.  I've also spoken to people who are either sitting on their couch working (not ideal) or working on a dressing table, again not ideal.  I do think that as more companies realise that working from home is a productive and efficient way to work, there will be different demands on the types of property people buy, and also the location - there is less need to be in commutable distance to the office.  I'm sure there will be an evolving market in "work from home furniture".    Software development is, on the whole a solitary business, so there are reduced distractions at home, which enables the guys to sink into their work, and solve problems.  As easy as it is to work longer hours, I always encourage staff to ensure they take breaks, get out for some exercise, give the mind a rest - which can also be the best time to solve problems.    Camera's for meetings are useful, it does help with the social/informal chat in a meeting, even if its just noticing that someone's had a hair cut, or as sometimes happened with m during lock-down, my daughter would join in the meeting!  You can also see when people are paying attention or not too I really like the idea of Mob Programming, as you are saying there so many benefits to it, both professionally, and socially. Kind regards Iain

Hi Helen,  Interesting question. Honestly, I think the answers from my experience aren't significantly different from my answers for co-located teams. Superficially, making sure teams have the right levels of equipment, have a comfortable working environment etc are all just as important, if not more so, for remote teams. Communication is critical, making sure people get the right amount of contact with people, not only for doing their job but so they don't feel isolated. I think cameras on for remote calls help with that a lot, albeit not everyone feels comfortable with that, so ultimately user's choice with that. Last point would be about trying to ensure your team is able to operate asynchronously where possible. If people have to wait for colleagues to perform tasks before they can complete their current task, you can end up with blockers. So supporting people to do parallel tasks is useful. As is helping people understand the priority of any blocking task against whatever they're currently doing. Code reviews would be a good example of that for a software specific example. Nobody likes waiting 3 days for a pull request if that's how you work, or having nobody to pair with if that's your preference.  That's off the top of my head. I don't think any of it is specifically tech focused though, I think that would apply to any environment.  Hope that's in some way useful. I'd love to read your piece once done.  Regards  Dave

I mean, if you talk to businesses 95% ? will present some form of communication issue as being a barrier - so I suppose it's nothing newly specific to covid.¬† I think we (at Parker Software) are quite lucky that most of our staff have been able to mentally adapt quite well to the working from home, and that we had a strong business already so people aren't worried on that front.
Thanks Daniel, that's interesting.¬† Yes the need to be more pro-active with communication seems to be a common theme.

We've found the biggest way to get the positive results is through transparency - sharing out the data that we are using to track the team performance and making it more of a team "result".¬†¬†  I think the biggest problems we've had are around being able to see the non-work problems people are having - when someone is in the office you can tell if they are responding differently to usual, and ask some questions or offer them support - when they are remote you have to be a lot more proactive with the questioning, and some people don't respond well to this.  Poor communication and feedback seems to be the biggest demotivator - if one person on the team doesn't communicate well, it causes more of a problem when its remote, as I think the group doesn't automatically repair the problem by talking to them proactively, or working to setup some group meetings.  Hope this helps.

HI Helen, Sure! I think you need ¬†WIFI Access Points in a few places, depending how direct in the vertical and horizontal plane your access point is. WIFI will travel through plaster and brick ¬†to some degree in the horizontal and vertical plane but the problem comes when you try to access a WIFI point at an angle through the house as the direct beam might have to travel through twice of three times the thickness of wall as it is going through at an angle.  There are a few options but I've not tried them as I use Google hubs which communicate via radio in a Mesh network but as you have CAT6 cable it's better to use this.  I think you might be able to use the Google routers as WAPs as they each have an ethernet port. There is a really cheap device that I have used that seems to have WAP mode - see TPLInk - very cheap -¬†https://www.tp-link.com/uk/home-networking/3g-usb-adapter/tl-wr802n/  I think you would need to have a multi point standard router as your hub and then use the CAT6 to fan out from each port to multiple of these WIFI Apps.  These are quite cheap so not sure of how reliable or performant they are but I'm sure there are other similar devices on the market at a higher price point.  Steve

Hi Helen, hope your well.  Sounds very much like my house. So The fact that you have cat6 everywhere is excellent and all you basically need is a WiFi router  plugged in. You can get these cheap, basically netgear or the like will work however if you want something smart that means you have a single WiFi name for each ap and your device seamlessly moves between them I can recommend unifi kit. Not cheap by any means but works well as all the access points pretend to be the same WiFi rather than 3 seperate ones. Although having cheap seperate device with three different name ie frontroom, upstairs and kitchen works OK. All this stuff is pretty much plug and play and the unifi kit is app driven with good instructions, but I recon you do either setup.

Hi Dave, can I pick your technical brains about the best way to get a decent wifi signal everywhere in my big old Edwardian 3 storey house?   I have a Cat6 ethernet link wired to every room, and a Virgin media cable link with a Hub3 thing for internet located inside the front door - the expensive Virgin Media package which  promises 200Mb internet speed (which it does on the ethernet link) but wifi is ok at front of the house, but gets weak on the top floor and non existant at the back of the house.  I have a wifi booster to try and solve that which manages to boost the wifi signal to just about visible at the back of the house, but the signal strength is poor, and it is basically boosting the wifi system over the airwaves.  So, given that I have ethernet in every room that gives pretty good internet connection over the wire, is there a thing that I can buy and plug into that ethernet at the back of the house that would create a good wifi signal there?   If so, what would that thing be called? and how hard would it be for a non-hardware-literate person to set up? ;)

SUBJECT: RE: Koenig Training
CONTENT: Hi Mark,  I had a good experience all round.  I spent 4 weeks in India, and got the training and 4 certifications I came for, for less than the cost of the same training in the uk, and so much more of an experience.  Because I had requested to train in the mountains in shimla, they flew me a trainer out from Delhi and I ended up with one on one training for the price of a group course, and also, they were very flexible about adapting the material covered to include things I requested in addition to the basic course material.  My trainer was excellent and would spend his evenings researching things so he could make sure he taught me something I didn't know every day (he was half my age and I had been programming as long as he had been alive! But he succeeded most days :) the facilities in the training venue, machines, Internet etc were good, but in the student apartments we sometimes had to reboot the router, and it was a bit flaky the odd day, but it was mostly ok.  I may do it again at some point. Kind Regards helen

CONTENT: Hello Luke,  Thanks for contacting me.      I'm not currently in the phase of trying to build leads from the Chaos website just yet, but I can see possible potential for the future.  I'm fully committed until Christmas at the moment.    I read through your website though and your software sounds interesting. I may be interested in looking at your partnering programme in the coming year. However, I couldn't find anywhere that gave me any pricing information.      When I do technology consultancy I generally work with solo-preneurs, startups, not-for-profits or new businesses who are just starting out and don't have a large sales/marketing/IT budget.  I provide them guidance, help with IT, websites and suchlike.  This often includes Google Analytics and so your product might be an interesting option for some clients.    However, Google Analytics is free, so I'd need to know what your pricing structure is like to see if it would fit with my target client base. Are you able to give me a ballpark idea, or point me to a relevant place on your website that I've missed?    Kind Regards  Helen

SUBJECT: Chaos On Toast‚Äôs website visitors

I am certain that you would benefit from having a demo and a week‚Äôs free trial of the software, so you can see for yourself how effective this tool would be for your company. Please email me at lukeporter@leadforensics.com. It would be great to hear your thoughts.   Best wishes,   Luke

The Project had a somewhat ‚Äòiterative‚Äô approach, and as not all of the detail was spec‚Äôd Helen played a big part in the design, producing web pages that were neat, user friendly and intuitive, and any updates to the database were accurate and well thought through. SUBJECT: RE: Defence Academy
CONTENT: Helen,    Thank you very much for the email and your feedback and comments.  Both Iain and I felt you had some good management experience which is what the team needs togehter with your technical skills.  Something I do not have to the depth of your technical ability.      You interviewed vey well and came across as a strong candidate.  Iain and I both feel that the team needs some stability as they have been without a direct manager for almost twelve months.  We had an internal candidate who was appointed, but unfortunately was head hunted after only a month or two in the role.  We now need the stability to provide direction and focus the team and felt that a nine month contract would not provide the solution we are looking for.    I have spoken to Nabeel and agreed that we would certainly keep you in mind if we needed someone on a short to medium term project.    Thank you for your openess and honesty and I wish you the best in both your sporting and technical aspirations.    Regards  Michael

SUBJECT: Defence Academy
CONTENT: Dear Michael Nottle,  I really enjoyed meeting you, Ian and Colin at the Defence Academy last week.    I appreciated the positive feedback I received from Nabeel Haq, and I'm sorry to turn down the opportunity to take up a permanent position with you.  I would have loved to work with you for a fixed period of 9 months, and felt I could contribute a great deal to the team, as well as being able to plan a controlled handover to a successor, or mentor someone existing who may be able to grow into the role.     However, I do not feel it would be right for me to take a permanent position at this time, knowing that I would want to take 3 months off next winter, and probably each year for the foreseeable future.  The only fair solution for my employers and myself that I can see is to stick with my decision to work on a contracting basis.     I have decided to balance my life by spending 2-3 months per year in the Alps teaching snowboarding,  every year while I'm fit enough to do it.  I have been training towards this for the last 2 years, initially via a sabbatical from my previous job.  I find doing this not only keeps me physically fit and healthy, it makes such a refreshing change after 9 months of intensive work in software development, and I come back to work feeling re-invigorated and enthused to take up the mental challenges again with renewed energy.      I appreciate that if you have found a suitable candidate who can take the position permanently; this may be a better solution for you.  However if you find that you are having difficulty retaining staff at the right level, or if at some point in the future you have a need for additional resource between the months of April and December, I would be very glad to hear from you.    Kind Regards  Helen Abell

Hi Ruth,   Thank you.  Yes it was redundancy, sort of by mutual agreement... they're merging the development teams across Tony's world of Parking/Police & Public Protection under one manager.  I didn't fancy spending my life driving between Bath, Luton and Chesterfield though so decided to take redundancy instead of going through the normal shenanigans with two of us applying for the new job.  I've known for a while but it's taken ages to get the message out and ended up being 3 days before I left!    It was all a bit of a shock at first, it's never nice when this happens to you.  I'm coming round now though and now starting to look forward to a change of direction.  I was with Flare/Civica 8 years and starting to feel quite institutionalised!     Linked in has been pretty good though, even though I have hardly anything on it, I've had all sorts of random contacts, although not what I'm looking for yet, but it makes me feel quite hopeful!  I even got a headhunting call from  Google!  But it was a permanent job and in London.  Even so, it was a nice feeling.    How are you doing?  Have you found anything you're interested in yet?    I'm looking at various options at the moment, and will probably go into consultancy in the short term.  Mainly because I want to spend January to March 2012 getting my next level snowboard instructor certificate in Bulgaria!.
